If the user then stays local to his system, the DC will not hear from him again. It will have no idea whether he stays logged on for 2 seconds or 2 weeks When he selects local machine, then authentication is local, and the DC is not involved. Think of the localmachine as a domain - which can only include one PC In a normal business setup, authentication takes place at the DC is it is available. However, Win NT, W2000, XP, and so on can cache a login once the DC has authenticated it, in case the DC is not avilable later domain controller Not sure how to answer; there are many things to be conscious of Are you thinking that if we make an ACL on the local machine hold a global group, how would the user access things protected by that global group when the DC is unavailable? The answer is: when a username/password is authenticated at a DC, the DC sends back a token that basically says 'authentication passed; user is a member of the following domain groups' The client machine caches that token which includes the list of groups And that's how a cached login can access a local resource protected by an acl including DOMAIN\SOMEGROUP (better way to put it: an ACE specifying DOMAIN\SOMEGROUP) I suspect that more specifically it says don't create local groups on the DC and then use them on resource servers or client machines This always confuses people.
